  "doc_id": "38969",
  "text": "Histone acetylation is a process in which acetyl coenzyme A transfers acetyl to the lysine residues of core histone N terminal domains under the catalysis of histone acetyltransferases (HATs). Histone acetylation can not only neutralize the positive charge in histone, but also reduce the affinity between histone and negatively charged phosphate in DNA. Therefore, it can lose the chromatin structure and activate gene transcription activity. In contrast, histone deacetylase (HDAC) mediates the reverse process and silences some specific genes [CITATION_1] . It has been demonstrated that histone acetylation was lower in the temporal lobe of AD patients than in aged controls [CITATION_2] . However, another study has found increased acetyl and total levels in postmortem AD brains [CITATION_3] .",
